Hygiene of an ArgoCD-built automation at a scale

GitOps is pretty new and quickly became a popular approach for managing Kubernetes clusters. Properly implemented makes daily work with the cluster much easier, incorrectly done can be harmful.

Knowledge about the theory and about the experiences of others is a key to introducing GitOps in your organization. This approach additionally requires always keeping the team up-to-date with changes to automation that is responsible to provision systems using higher permissions.

I will try to cover there more advanced cases than a few basic good practices repeated across various blogs. The following points are written from my experience.

Know your use case

ArgoCD is different fromkubectl apply, it’s a fully-featured machine that operates on your cluster, in most cases with cluster-admin privileges.

The controller is merging YAMLs, applying, deleting, can be configured to ignore selected fields, can respect internal RBAC to disallow creation of particular resources depending on the resource type or GIT repository those are coming from.

It is up to you to use it correctly, it’s just a tool.

1. Split automation into smaller pieces, even if there would be thousands of Application tiles. ArgoCD will handle it

Knowing your use case and splitting automation into smaller pieces allows you to precisely limit the scope of operations in the context of every automation.

  • Separate things by scope — How you would work with it?
    Example:
    — Prod-app1 (deployed in CI/CD process)
    — Dev-app1 (deployed in CI/CD process)
    — resourceQuotas-app1 (automatic sync, often bumped to give more resources)
    — namespace+pv-app1 (manual sync, be careful there, no pruning)
    — kyvernoPolicies (manual sync, as sync can invoke a large-scale scanning operation)
  • Deploy developed applications separately from infrastructural things like Namespaces, LimitRanges to ensure nobody than the administrator can deploy such objects and to make sure those critical objects won't be wiped accidentally, that’s a bit rephrase of the previous point
  • Try to split by repository, ArgoCD does not like too many managed resources in a single repository — it will work, but you will need to adjust settings for better performance

Example of a complete system automation design — every line is separate automation:

1) “CD factory”: ApplicationSet + GIT files generator + helm creates Namespaces, Roles and installs ArgoCD per group of Namespaces (optionally if you need such granulation). There you should disable resource pruning and possibly disable automatic synchronization to carefully deploy your changes

2) “Quotas management”: ApplicationSet + Kustomize + GIT directory generator for managing per-namespace Resource Quotas, Network Policies and other restrictions. There you can use resources whitelisting to prevent mistakes, additionally enable automatic synchronization, pruning, drift fixing and orphaned resources detection which will show all resources created “by hand”

3) “CI Pipelines factory”: ApplicationSet + SCM provider generator + helm to automatically discover repositories in Git, associate them to per-team AppProject to restrict permissions and connect as Applications to synchronize applications produced by development teams.

Prepared generic Helm Chart can automatically generate permissions per-team, and deploy dev/test/prod namespaces for each team. Additionally there CI/CD Tekton pipelines could be installed per-team namespace in Kubernetes.

4) “Repository importer”: With App Of Apps pattern you can install anything by just adding a new Application file in the synchronized directory, no manual steps involved.

2. Analyse what happens when a change was made

Smaller automation can be easily tested, you need to identify resources that have ownerReferences and what happens if those resources or their parents will disappear.

Use dynamically concatenated names of namespaces and other crucial resources very carefully, especially when using Helm as in complex automation the person may change only an inconspicuous value that may “rename” your namespace by deleting it and re-creating again with a changed name.

Example of a risky construction:

---
apiVersion: v1
kind: Namespace
name: {{ .Values.env.SYSTEM_NAME }}-{{ .Values.environmentName }}

Now imagine that your teammate will just fix a typo in the environment name.

If you need to use constructions like this, always disable resource pruning for resources that have dependencies using annotation argocd.argoproj.io/sync-options: Prune=false or by disabling the prune in kind: Application using .syncOptions.prune=false then resources will be shown as out-of-sync for manual pruning or reverting.

In case of ApplicationSetmake sure you use option .syncPolicy.preserveResourcesOnDeletion=true when your generated ArgoCD’s Application are creating namespaces and other resources that have dependencies you would not like to accidentally wipe.

Orphaned resources you will have to clean up manually in this case, you can always import them back by doing a commit rollback or by creating an Application that will import them.

Test your ApplicationSet settings on an example project by deleting directories or files, and changing their names — if using GIT generator, or manipulate values when using List generator, see what happens.

Remember: Nothing will save your resources from recursive deletion, when you manually click “Delete” on ArgoCD’s Application, type in it’s name for confirmation and press ok. The prune settings will not help there as deletion is not a part of synchronization process

3. Adjust synchronization settings to use case

Sounds pretty obvious, but sometimes it is not. When your automation have a limited scope of what could be synchronized, to which cluster, which namespace then you can securely enable comfortable GitOps features like pruning, automatic synchronization, or auto healing.

Critical resources can be first reviewed before synchronizing to be able to decide for example about pruning no longer managed resources that remained after the previous release.

Resources that have dependencies like namespaces or ArgoCD applications could be defined with an annotation that prevents resources from pruning, but this will not work in case when our kind: Application generated by Helm or ApplicationSet will disappear.

Ignore selected fields — the most popular example is to tell ArgoCD to not overwrite desired replicas number in deployments when this number in the live application environment is controlled dynamically by an autoscaler. You may want to use this feature when synchronizing Projects or Namespaces on OpenShift to not lose very important annotations that OpenShift adds like the information about the UID range.

4. Avoid YAML files containing multiple resources

It’s incredible simple to make a mistake in a YAML file containing multiple resources — simply delete the “- - -” separator and the resource lower on the list will overwrite the previous one from the top.

5. Use FailOnSharedResource

This option protect partially against incorrectly done copy & paste, by checking if there are multiple resources of the same combination of Name + Namespace + ApiVersion + Kind.

If this option is enabled, then the Application will not be synchronized and you will see an error.

6. Least privileges

There are a few cases when privilege separation can help.

a) Multi-tenancy use-case
Using multiple repositories, where different people have access to you should pre-create kind: AppProject and kind: Application that would point to repositories where developers has write access. Such kind: AppProject should disallow switching namespace, cluster or creating resources like ClusterRoles , Namespaces or NetworkPolicies

Use SSO groups to assign groups of users to kind: AppProject , in effect they would be able to see and synchronize only selected kind: Application

Alternatively use the ArgoCD operator to create an ArgoCD instance for each team, it’s for those who require a maximum level of separation.

b) Creating secure automation
This case was already described in previous points, it is about making sure that accidental file creation, deletion, or a name change would not trigger unwanted consequences.

c) Installing resources from external repositories (e.g. using Helm)
Always when you install new operators, controllers, and infrastructural applications - close them inside an AppProject and specify restrictions.

This allows us to avoid mistakes like:
- Installing Helm Chart into the incorrectly typed namespace
- Usage of values that are creating extra things like ClusterRoles, while we do not want to those ClusterRoles to be installed
- Managing unwanted types of resources e.g. namespaces (which can lead to cascade deletion, when a Helm release will be uninstalled)
- Somebody made a mistake with the namespace name in one of resources

7. Separate installation of Custom Resources Definitions from applications

When deleting a CRD all resources matching that CRD will also get deleted. To make sure your data stays in the cluster, even if you delete a Helm release is to separate those things. Some Helm Charts have an option to not install CRDs. It may be worth installing CRDs separately using Kustomize’s remote resource fetching option pointing to a tagged release.

8. Use instance banners

Always set an information banner when you have multiple ArgoCD instances, it would help you and your comrades to not get lost in your probably complex system.

Summary

Implementing GitOps requires more effort than installing ArgoCD and connecting your repository to synchronize every change. A correctly done setup must be carefully thought before it gets propagated to your Kubernetes clusters across all availability zones. Your GitOps tool will propagate not only your regular changes but also typos and other mistakes across all clusters in all availability zones unless you reduce the scope and design your automation properly.
